# The Year of Mindful Purpose (part 1)
## A reflection on purpose, meaning, and mindfulness in a world constantly dragging us forward.

![](../../Meta/Attachments/arno-senoner-Nt490aWJEYw-unsplash(1).jpg)

> [!QUOTE]
> “Let go of your mind and then be mindful. 
> Close your ears and listen!”
> *--Rumi*

## Mindless without purpose

If the unexamined life is not worth living, is the over examined life worth living twice? Not even Socrates could answer that question, as he barely got to live once before being forced to drink poison by the state. Although I'm not going to be facing trial for corrupting today's youth anytime soon, I do often wonder what it means to live a fulfilled life. I often struggle with the feeling that I'm not doing what I'm _supposed to_ be doing. That I'm not spending my energy on the right things and using time in the right way. As my thirties draw to a close, with time marching faster each year, I can't help but wonder, *is this is it?* Will my life be largely measured by puttering around in my basement on whatever projects strike my fancy at the moment, attention drawn ramshackle to the nearest endeavor that brings me some moderate amount of pleasure, or can I live with _purpose_? And if so, what does it mean to live with purpose?

I need a _Walden_ moment - but not in the sense that I have to shun society for a cabin in the woods and shed modern convenience. Rather, I need an inner cabin and metaphorical woods to retreat to. The mountain of my mind follows me everywhere. "Wherever you go, there you are" is an old adage of dubious origin, popular in 12-step circles, with a distinctly Zen feeling to it (not coincidentally also the title of a 1994 bestselling book on mindfulness meditation by Jon Kabat-Zinn). I can't get away from myself, so I need to learn to make peace with myself. Put a ceasefire to the constant striving to be something and try to learn to live with myself as I am.

## Mind within matter

I decided that 2023 would be the year of **mindful purpose**. How do I define mindful purpose? Mindfulness is the state of being fully aware, present and engaged without being distracted, lost in thought, or trying to do two things at once. Being present in the moment and fully participating in whatever you're doing. One can be mindfully engaged in anything, including activities which bring you no benefit, which leads to the concept of purposefulness. 

What I mean by purpose is living with my actions and activities in direct alignment with my goals and objectives. Purpose is the motivational force behind right action, right speech, and right concentration. I want to recognize my purpose and then set out to engage mindfully in it. I want to live a purposefully mindful existence, and a mindfully purposeful existence, and so I have set out to attempt that for a year.

Practically speaking, what does this mean for me? How do I apply the concept of mindful purpose to my daily life? How do I cultivate mindfulness and cultivate purpose? 

## Cultivating Mindfulness Through Meditation

Daily meditation gives us the ability to practice mindfulness. Part of the intention of a daily meditation practice is for this mindfulness to extend to other areas of our lives naturally, as we learn to grow in our mindful practice. Jon Kabat-Zinn himself said: 

> [!QUOTE]
> \[M]indfulness is a whole repertoire of formal meditative practices aimed at cultivating moment-to-moment nonjudgmental awareness.
> *--[Everyday Mindfulness with Jon Kabat-Zinn - Mindful](https://www.mindful.org/everyday-mindfulness-with-jon-kabat-zinn/)*

Full disclosure: I have a bit of a history with meditation. I have meditated off and on for 10 years, loosely following the Zen tradition, but unfortunately I have had a hard time being consistent in my practice, which partially defeats the purpose. 

To cultivate mindfulness, I will meditate daily this year. I started on January 1. I sit in the morning, when the house is quiet, and I'm the only one awake. Buddhist monks are known to sit and meditate in the middle of the market on occasion. Zen meditation is not meant, to remove us from this world, but [to wake us up to it](Awake%20(Zen).md).

>![](data:image/png;base64,)
--Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@izzombol?utm_source=unsplash&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=creditCopyText">Márton Szalai</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com/photos/TrY_YA-xx4o?utm_source=unsplash&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=creditCopyText">Unsplash</a>

I have my favorite zafu and zabuton (meditation cushion and mat) and my favorite meditation timer app I love to use (I'll spare you the plug for it). I sit in the lotus position and focus on my breathing, tongue touching the roof of my mouth, back straight and hands in my lap, tips of my thumbs touching. This is just what works for me. Everyone has their own practice. And it doesn't matter if you have the fancy cushions, or the ideal environment, or the right time of day, the important thing is to do it: sit and be mindful of the present moment.

## Mindfulness and Acceptance

Regular meditation can have impacts beyond the zafu and zabuton. In the past, when I've made meditation a regular part of my daily routine, I find myself paying more attention to my breath throughout the day. You can learn a lot about yourself from your breath. If I'm breathing short, shallow rapid breaths, then I might be anxious and not realize it. Holding my breath subconsciously is a sign that I'm holding onto stress in my body. 

If I'm active in my mindfulness meditation practice, when I'm holding onto stress or anxiety, I can simply acknowledge those states of being. I can accept them for what they are and accept myself as I am. I don't have to fight my anxiety and my stress. What good does fighting them do, anyway? Rather, I can accept them nonjudgmentally.

>![](data:image/png;base64,)
>Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@peterburdon?utm_source=unsplash&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=creditCopyText">Peter Burdon</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com/photos/vuVQ5bMQBN0?utm_source=unsplash&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=creditCopyText">Unsplash</a>
  
I suffer from an anxiety disorder, like 31% of U.S. adults will at some point in their lives. In a twisted way, I've learned to love my anxiety in some ways. It's part of what makes me unique. I wouldn't be the same person if I didn't suffer from anxiety. I can still often lose myself in the middle of a panic attack, but if I'm active in my meditation practice, I am better about simply acknowledging the panic, observing its actions on my body, feeling myself as from the outside in, like a quiet observer. In those moments, I can accept the panic without judging it, and without judging myself. This is just who I am, and that's OK. Paradoxically, when I'm mindful of my anxiety and panic and accept them nonjudgmentally, they tend to dissipate. I can observe the panic washing over my body and realize that it's not a constant feeling. It ebbs and flows, and moves from one part of my body to another.

## Mindfulness Through Journaling

> [!QUOTE]
> A diary is useful during conscious, intentional, and painful spiritual evolutions.
> *--André Gide, Journals: 1889-1913*

Beyond diligent meditation practice, I will also be journaling rigorously throughout the year. Journaling is a great way to establish mindfulness around your thoughts and emotions. For example, I will be tracking my overall mood, anxiety, depression, and energy levels on a scale of 1-10 on a daily basis. Additionally, I have been recording 3 words to describe my emotions during the day. This forces me to examine my feelings on a daily basis and better be mindful of my inner experience. Beyond this, I'm also tracking a few bullet points about the day, the amount of sleep I got, the amount of time I spent meditating, and whether I exercised. Keeping these journals is about more than posterity. Writing down your thoughts and feelings on a regular basis can have tremendous benefits to your mental health by reducing ruminating thoughts, giving you a chance to unload mentally, and granting you the ability to take stock of the day. 

Journaling is something that I experimented with a little last year. In that time, it amazed me to see that days I thought were a total waste actually amounted to something when I sat down and cataloged the day’s events. I also noticed that my depths of depression had peaks and valleys. My mood wasn't so much a monolithic, unchanging entity as it was fluid: changing throughout the day, throughout the week; developing from the patchwork of a million brief interactions and experiences that made up each day. Being mindful of this helps me to understand the fleeting nature of the bad moments and remember that they pass, that all we have is the ever-changing present. I want to live in the present.
